</h3><p class="sc-kAkozD iOjmJ pf-24_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Performing CPR involves direct physical contact and often, the exposure to bodily fluids. Ineffective hygiene measures can increase the risk of cross-contamination and transmission of infections, including viral pathogens such as HBV, HCV, and HIV. Statistics from health authorities highlight the significance of adhering to hygiene protocols, with studies indicating that proper sanitation can reduce the risk of infection transmission by up to 80%.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-jXbVAB kNtuek pf-26_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-bDoQz cmNGeH pf-27_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cmaqZA fXrIOS pf-28_ pf-heading-1-h3">Understanding key definitions</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-dPZUdm cBqcmb pf-30_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-31_ pf-text-1"><strong>Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR)</strong> - A lifesaving technique used in emergencies when someone's heartbeat or breathing has stopped.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-33_ pf-text-1"><strong>Hygiene during CPR</strong> - Refers to the practices involved in preventing infection during CPR, including the use of barriers like face masks and gloves.



</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-jXbVAB kNtuek pf-35_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-bDoQz cmNGeH pf-36_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cmaqZA fXrIOS pf-37_ pf-heading-1-h3">Relevant legislation and regulations</h3><p class="sc-kAkozD iOjmJ pf-39_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">CPR training in the UK is guided by regulations from the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and recommendations by the Resuscitation Council (UK). These guidelines emphasise the importance of hygiene in CPR to prevent the transmission of infections. Compliance with these regulations is not just best practice—it is a requisite under the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974, which mandates adequate training and measures to ensure the health and safety of both rescuers and victims.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-jXbVAB kNtuek pf-41_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-bDoQz cmNGeH pf-42_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cmaqZA fXrIOS pf-43_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices in hygiene during CPR</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-dPZUdm cBqcmb pf-45_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-46_ pf-text-1"><strong>Use of personal protective equipment (PPE) </strong>- Gloves, masks, and protective eyewear should be worn during training and actual resuscitation attempts.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-48_ pf-text-1"><strong>Proper disposal of PPE </strong>- After performing CPR, all used PPE should be disposed of safely and hygienically to prevent contamination.






</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-50_ pf-text-1"><strong>Regular sanitisation</strong> - CPR manikins used in training should be cleaned and disinfected after each use, adhering to manufacturers' guidelines and infection control protocols.







</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-jXbVAB kNtuek pf-52_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-bDoQz cmNGeH pf-53_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cmaqZA fXrIOS pf-54_ pf-heading-1-h3">Implementing effective training strategies</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-dPZUdm cBqcmb pf-56_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-57_ pf-text-1"><strong>Incorporate hygiene protocols in CPR training</strong> - Educators should integrate hygiene practices into the CPR curriculum, ensuring that trainees understand their importance and demonstrate proficiency.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-eBHgEO eUYsjc pf-59_ pf-text-1"><strong>Simulation-based learning</strong> - Utilising advanced manikins and simulations to teach correct hygiene techniques can enhance the learning experience and preparedness of healthcare providers.






</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-jXbVAB kNtuek pf-61_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-bDoQz cmNGeH pf-62_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cmaqZA fXrIOS pf-63_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommendations
</h3><p class="sc-kAkozD iOjmJ pf-65_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Organisations involved in providing CPR training must ensure that their courses are comprehensive, up-to-date, and compliant with current legislation. It is recommended that training programmes are regularly reviewed and updated in line with the latest guidelines from the Resuscitation Council (UK) and HSE. All training materials emphasise the importance of hygiene during CPR. Continuous professional development (CPD) opportunities are provided to keep healthcare providers aware of the latest hygiene practices in CPR.
